06:33.340 --> 06:34.560
This is Daryl Lane.

06:34.660 --> 06:35.260
And Bill Vernon.

06:35.840 --> 06:37.780
Locus is Science Fiction's leading trade magazine.

06:38.040 --> 06:40.540
It's written for professional writers and for serious readers.

06:41.060 --> 06:43.600
The professionals get information on prospective markets.

06:44.140 --> 06:47.920
The readers get up-to-date information on reviews, conventions and forthcoming books.

06:48.280 --> 06:49.780
But Locus has its roots in fandom.

06:50.280 --> 06:54.660
Charles Brown, its founder, editor and publisher, tells us how he discovered science fiction fandom

06:54.660 --> 06:56.360
soon after he began reading science fiction.

06:57.080 --> 07:00.440
Oh, I started reading science fiction.

07:00.460 --> 07:04.120
I was reading a founding in the 40s.

07:04.620 --> 07:08.620
And I started fandom all around 1949.

07:11.160 --> 07:19.960
By finding conventions listed in one of the magazines, Super Science Story, or something like that.

07:20.660 --> 07:23.580
I was to the 1950s convention.

07:24.300 --> 07:26.520
I was 12 years old when I went to this convention.

07:27.920 --> 07:29.220
I had a wonderful time.

07:29.340 --> 07:33.180
And I met all these old men, like Fred Cole and Bester Del Rey.

07:33.420 --> 07:34.040
They were old.

07:34.780 --> 07:36.260
Most of them were pushing 30.

07:38.700 --> 07:41.580
When you're 12, you don't think anybody's ever going to reach 30.

07:43.600 --> 07:45.040
It's really up there.

07:45.040 --> 07:52.040
And now it's frightening because I met two other people and they're considered the same age pretty much.

07:54.580 --> 07:56.680
But double-sword, silver fandom.

07:57.860 --> 08:01.040
And I put out my first fan scene about 1951.

08:03.480 --> 08:07.760
Dropped out again when I was in college.

08:08.320 --> 08:09.060
And things like that.

08:09.260 --> 08:12.020
And then she went back to the late 50s.

08:12.760 --> 08:15.680
So Brown has been involved in fandom since 1950.

08:16.340 --> 08:18.780
We asked him how fandom has changed through the years.

08:21.000 --> 08:24.300
1950, there were all these 13-year-old kids and I was right there.

08:25.740 --> 08:27.520
I was talking to Harlan Ellison today.

08:27.800 --> 08:35.020
He said the one thing he just came back from Australia, he was just a monarchy, an Australian convention.

08:36.400 --> 08:39.100
It's just like the American fandom of the 50s.

08:39.100 --> 08:41.940
There were all these 13-year-old kids and no women.

08:42.880 --> 08:46.740
They were all very sincere, very bright, and very socially inept.

08:48.320 --> 08:50.600
It's a pretty well-fandomed and most nice kid.

08:59.300 --> 09:01.240
Annually Brown conducts the Locust Poll.

09:01.680 --> 09:06.620
The Poll is a tally of readers' responses to such topics as favorite novels, short stories, artists, and so on.

09:06.620 --> 09:08.720
And it reveals some personal information as well.

09:09.260 --> 09:12.360
One bit of information is that the average Locust reader seems to be getting older.

09:13.140 --> 09:15.300
Our audience is always going to gotten older.

09:16.660 --> 09:18.960
Mainly because the audience has stayed with us.

09:19.760 --> 09:24.880
About 80% of the people who read Locust in 1968 still read Locust.

09:26.000 --> 09:29.420
Which of course keeps raising the ages.

09:30.920 --> 09:33.340
There are some new people, but not that many.

09:34.660 --> 09:39.220
What are the changes of course in the magazine?

09:39.420 --> 09:43.700
The magazine is no longer aimed at a teenage fan.

09:44.640 --> 09:46.020
It's aimed at professionals.

09:48.400 --> 09:52.020
Of course it means we attract the older professionals.

09:53.560 --> 09:59.620
I think there are probably no more than two or three professionals who are not the providers.

10:00.620 --> 10:03.320
Brown has been publishing Locust for 16 years.

10:03.720 --> 10:06.060
We ask him if he still gets satisfaction from it.

10:06.560 --> 10:09.240
I was looking at the Blue Lines for the new issue today.

10:09.480 --> 10:10.540
It was very exciting.

10:10.740 --> 10:13.260
The first time you see it come together.

10:13.520 --> 10:14.980
You see all the photographs together.

10:16.340 --> 10:18.620
All the stories in one place.

10:19.460 --> 10:20.160
The pieces.

10:23.820 --> 10:26.780
You still got a real thrill when you hold that first copy.

10:28.600 --> 10:30.880
I'll get my final copy tomorrow.

10:32.260 --> 10:36.220
I'll be down at the printer 8.30 in the morning watching it run off.

10:36.380 --> 10:38.900
I'll pull out a copy myself and stay put together.

10:40.220 --> 10:41.700
And then I'll have another copy.

10:42.620 --> 10:44.640
We'll have more with Charles Brown on our next show.

