Look inside the front page and you'll find a small box entitled Editorial Matters.

12:32.360 --> 12:34.800
In the editorial you'll find, among other acknowledgments,

12:35.040 --> 12:38.280
the names of people who helped collate, fold, and mail the copies of the issue.

12:38.460 --> 12:41.820
We asked Charles Brown, the founder, editor, and publisher of Locust,

12:41.820 --> 12:45.320
to describe how a typical Locust issue is put together prior to mailing.

12:46.000 --> 12:47.760
People come over to mail them.

12:48.000 --> 12:50.420
Well, it's not collated. It's mailing books.

12:51.540 --> 12:53.960
We get the picture back from the printer in the afternoon

12:53.960 --> 12:58.820
and one or two people may show up and help us put stamps on first-class copies.

13:00.440 --> 13:02.520
Then a larger crowd comes in the evening.

13:04.000 --> 13:09.300
You see over there's said dinner and sit around and drink and put out...

13:11.860 --> 13:14.860
We put all the labels on the thing and put it outside the order.

13:15.920 --> 13:18.280
And the chronological order by zip code.

13:18.620 --> 13:19.880
And there's fact-dots in.

13:21.240 --> 13:23.580
Usually we finish by about 10.30 or 11.

13:23.720 --> 13:26.080
Everybody sits around and talks about Science Fiction.

13:27.840 --> 13:30.420
Very few of the people are of what you call science.

13:30.580 --> 13:33.600
There almost all writers.

13:33.840 --> 13:36.960
In fact, we had a contest last year.

13:36.960 --> 13:39.280
It's the best first novel by a Locust co-lager.

13:40.040 --> 13:41.560
We did have three nominees.

13:44.420 --> 13:51.160
As far as I can tell, probably about 90% of the Locusts are collated with at least one novel.

13:51.760 --> 13:54.700
Locust has grown from a small fanzine to a professionally produced,

13:54.940 --> 13:56.360
nearly 50-page-long publication.

13:57.040 --> 13:59.500
We asked Brown if he plans to continue expanding Locusts.

13:59.660 --> 14:00.980
His answer may surprise you.

14:01.740 --> 14:03.620
Actually, I'd like to do the opposite.

14:03.620 --> 14:05.880
I do not want to expand the magazine at all.

14:06.020 --> 14:07.600
It will expand anyway. It always does.

14:08.900 --> 14:13.440
But I have no interest in doing a bigger magazine.

14:14.700 --> 14:18.680
In fact, I find a magazine too big now and the situation too bad.

14:20.380 --> 14:25.100
I really want to do a magazine for a limited number of people.

14:25.760 --> 14:27.860
Where I can do it all myself at home.

14:29.200 --> 14:34.760
I'm very frightened about getting to the point where I need a larger staff and an office.

14:36.660 --> 14:38.360
Everything is going at home right now.

14:39.760 --> 14:45.860
Some of the changes are always forced on us because there's more news that we feel we have to cover.

14:46.940 --> 14:50.740
As you probably noticed, we're doing a lot more international coverage lately.

14:52.800 --> 14:57.660
Covering the Soviet Union and the European Convention.

14:58.540 --> 15:00.960
And we've had articles on Chinese science.

15:03.440 --> 15:08.540
And I'm off to China next week to an other U.S. university,

15:08.780 --> 15:10.400
Shanghai, and South Korea, between there.

15:27.480 --> 15:29.640
Locust has caught seven Hugo awards so far.

15:29.880 --> 15:31.880
Is brown tiring and winning so many Hugo's?

15:32.540 --> 15:35.020
I don't get tired of winning them now. It's a lot of fun.

15:38.600 --> 15:41.500
There have been complaints but they don't bother me too much.

15:43.920 --> 15:48.060
I solved the problem with complaints. I sent Rachel out to pick them up every year.

15:51.820 --> 15:57.420
I won't stand for you as long as people vote for Locust, I'll gladly accept Hugo.

15:58.800 --> 16:01.540
Locust is a visible presence in the science fiction field.

16:01.740 --> 16:04.740
We asked Brown if it is a target for writers of crackpot letters.

16:05.540 --> 16:07.620
I tell you, I eat crackpot letters all the time.

16:09.360 --> 16:11.960
Really strange letters and we usually throw them out.

16:12.800 --> 16:18.020
The years we've collected all these really strange, far outlaid letters,

16:18.300 --> 16:20.840
ways waiting to publish them in a final issue.

16:21.540 --> 16:23.940
But it doesn't look like there will be a final issue with Locust.

16:25.260 --> 16:28.000
So there's no reason to keep them around anymore.

16:28.860 --> 16:31.920
If you're a serious science fiction fan, you need to be reading Locust.

